5571 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token in operand");
5572 return true;
5573 case AsmToken::Identifier: {
5574 // If we've seen a branch mnemonic, the next operand must be a label. This
5575 // is true even if the label is a register name. So "br r1" means branch to
5576 // label "r1".
5577 bool ExpectLabel = Mnemonic == "b" || Mnemonic == "bl";
5578 if (!ExpectLabel) {
5579 if (!tryParseRegisterWithWriteBack(Operands))
5580 return false;
5581 int Res = tryParseShiftRegister(Operands);
5582 if (Res == 0) // success
5583 return false;
5584 else if (Res == -1) // irrecoverable error
5585 return true;
5586 // If this is VMRS, check for the apsr_nzcv operand.
5587 if (Mnemonic == "vmrs" &&
5588 Parser.getTok().getString().equals_lower("apsr_nzcv")) {
5589 S = Parser.getTok().getLoc();
5590 Parser.Lex();
5591 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateToken("APSR_nzcv", S));
5592 return false;
5593 }
5594 }
5595
5596 // Fall though for the Identifier case that is not a register or a
5597 // special name.
5598 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
5599 }
5600 case AsmToken::LParen: // parenthesized expressions like (_strcmp-4)
5601 case AsmToken::Integer: // things like 1f and 2b as a branch targets
5602 case AsmToken::String: // quoted label names.
5603 case AsmToken::Dot: { // . as a branch target
5604 // This was not a register so parse other operands that start with an
5605 // identifier (like labels) as expressions and create them as immediates.
5606 const MCExpr *IdVal;
5607 S = Parser.getTok().getLoc();
5608 if (getParser().parseExpression(IdVal))
5609 return true;
5610 E = SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1);
5611 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateImm(IdVal, S, E));
5612 return false;
5613 }
5614 case AsmToken::LBrac:
5615 return parseMemory(Operands);
5616 case AsmToken::LCurly:
5617 return parseRegisterList(Operands, !Mnemonic.startswith("clr"));
5618 case AsmToken::Dollar:
5619 case AsmToken::Hash:
5620 // #42 -> immediate.
5621 S = Parser.getTok().getLoc();
5622 Parser.Lex();
5623
5624 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Colon)) {
5625 bool isNegative = Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Minus);
5626 const MCExpr *ImmVal;
5627 if (getParser().parseExpression(ImmVal))
5628 return true;
5629 const MCConstantExpr *CE = dyn_cast<MCConstantExpr>(ImmVal);
5630 if (CE) {
5631 int32_t Val = CE->getValue();
5632 if (isNegative && Val == 0)
5633 ImmVal = MCConstantExpr::create(std::numeric_limits<int32_t>::min(),
5634 getContext());
5635 }
5636 E = SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1);
5637 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateImm(ImmVal, S, E));
5638
5639 // There can be a trailing '!' on operands that we want as a separate
5640 // '!' Token operand. Handle that here. For example, the compatibility
5641 // alias for 'srsdb sp!, #imm' is 'srsdb #imm!'.
5642 if (Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Exclaim)) {
5643 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateToken(Parser.getTok().getString(),
5644 Parser.getTok().getLoc()));
5645 Parser.Lex(); // Eat exclaim token
5646 }
5647 return false;
5648 }
5649 // w/ a ':' after the '#', it's just like a plain ':'.
5650 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
5651
5652 case AsmToken::Colon: {
5653 S = Parser.getTok().getLoc();
5654 // ":lower16:" and ":upper16:" expression prefixes
5655 // FIXME: Check it's an expression prefix,
5656 // e.g. (FOO - :lower16:BAR) isn't legal.
5657 ARMMCExpr::VariantKind RefKind;
5658 if (parsePrefix(RefKind))
5659 return true;
5660
5661 const MCExpr *SubExprVal;
5662 if (getParser().parseExpression(SubExprVal))
5663 return true;
5664
5665 const MCExpr *ExprVal = ARMMCExpr::create(RefKind, SubExprVal,
5666 getContext());
5667 E = SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1);
5668 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateImm(ExprVal, S, E));
5669 return false;
5670 }
5671 case AsmToken::Equal: {
5672 S = Parser.getTok().getLoc();
5673 if (Mnemonic != "ldr") // only parse for ldr pseudo (e.g. ldr r0, =val)
5674 return Error(S, "unexpected token in operand");
5675 Parser.Lex(); // Eat '='
5676 const MCExpr *SubExprVal;
5677 if (getParser().parseExpression(SubExprVal))
5678 return true;
5679 E = SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1);
5680
5681 // execute-only: we assume that assembly programmers know what they are
5682 // doing and allow literal pool creation here
5683 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateConstantPoolImm(SubExprVal, S, E));
5684 return false;
5685 }
5686 }
5687}
5688
5689// parsePrefix - Parse ARM 16-bit relocations expression prefix, i.e.
5690// :lower16: and :upper16:.
5691bool ARMAsmParser::parsePrefix(ARMMCExpr::VariantKind &RefKind) {
5692 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser();
5693 RefKind = ARMMCExpr::VK_ARM_None;
5694
5695 // consume an optional '#' (GNU compatibility)
5696 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Hash))
5697 Parser.Lex();
5698
5699 // :lower16: and :upper16: modifiers
5700 assert(getLexer().is(AsmToken::Colon) && "expected a :");
5701 Parser.Lex(); // Eat ':'
5702
5703 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) {
5704 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "expected prefix identifier in operand");
5705 return true;
5706 }
5707
5708 enum {
5709 COFF = (1 << MCObjectFileInfo::IsCOFF),
5710 ELF = (1 << MCObjectFileInfo::IsELF),
5711 MACHO = (1 << MCObjectFileInfo::IsMachO),
5712 WASM = (1 << MCObjectFileInfo::IsWasm),
5713 };
5714 static const struct PrefixEntry {
5715 const char *Spelling;
5716 ARMMCExpr::VariantKind VariantKind;
5717 uint8_t SupportedFormats;
5718 } PrefixEntries[] = {
5719 { "lower16", ARMMCExpr::VK_ARM_LO16, COFF | ELF | MACHO },
5720 { "upper16", ARMMCExpr::VK_ARM_HI16, COFF | ELF | MACHO },
5721 };
5722
5723 StringRef IDVal = Parser.getTok().getIdentifier();
5724
5725 const auto &Prefix =
5726 std::find_if(std::begin(PrefixEntries), std::end(PrefixEntries),
5727 [&IDVal](const PrefixEntry &PE) {
5728 return PE.Spelling == IDVal;
5729 });
5730 if (Prefix == std::end(PrefixEntries)) {
5731 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected prefix in operand");
5732 return true;
5733 }
5734
5735 uint8_t CurrentFormat;
5736 switch (getContext().getObjectFileInfo()->getObjectFileType()) {
5737 case MCObjectFileInfo::IsMachO:
5738 CurrentFormat = MACHO;
5739 break;
5740 case MCObjectFileInfo::IsELF:
5741 CurrentFormat = ELF;
5742 break;
5743 case MCObjectFileInfo::IsCOFF:
5744 CurrentFormat = COFF;
5745 break;
5746 case MCObjectFileInfo::IsWasm:
5747 CurrentFormat = WASM;
5748 break;
5749 case MCObjectFileInfo::IsXCOFF:
5750 llvm_unreachable("unexpected object format");
5751 break;
5752 }
5753
5754 if (~Prefix->SupportedFormats & CurrentFormat) {
5755 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(),
5756 "cannot represent relocation in the current file format");
5757 return true;
5758 }
5759
5760 RefKind = Prefix->VariantKind;
5761 Parser.Lex();
5762
5763 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Colon)) {
5764 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token after prefix");
5765 return true;
5766 }
5767 Parser.Lex(); // Eat the last ':'
5768
5769 return false;
5770}
5771
5772/// Given a mnemonic, split out possible predication code and carry
5773/// setting letters to form a canonical mnemonic and flags.
5774//
5775// FIXME: Would be nice to autogen this.
5776// FIXME: This is a bit of a maze of special cases.
5777StringRef ARMAsmParser::splitMnemonic(StringRef Mnemonic,
5778 unsigned &PredicationCode,
5779 bool &CarrySetting,
5780 unsigned &ProcessorIMod,
5781 StringRef &ITMask) {
5782 PredicationCode = ARMCC::AL;
5783 CarrySetting = false;
5784 ProcessorIMod = 0;
5785
5786 // Ignore some mnemonics we know aren't predicated forms.
5787 //
5788 // FIXME: Would be nice to autogen this.
5789 if ((Mnemonic == "movs" && isThumb()) ||
5790 Mnemonic == "teq" || Mnemonic == "vceq" || Mnemonic == "svc" ||
5791 Mnemonic == "mls" || Mnemonic == "smmls" || Mnemonic == "vcls" ||
5792 Mnemonic == "vmls" || Mnemonic == "vnmls" || Mnemonic == "vacge" ||
5793 Mnemonic == "vcge" || Mnemonic == "vclt" || Mnemonic == "vacgt" ||
5794 Mnemonic == "vaclt" || Mnemonic == "vacle" || Mnemonic == "hlt" ||
5795 Mnemonic == "vcgt" || Mnemonic == "vcle" || Mnemonic == "smlal" ||
5796 Mnemonic == "umaal" || Mnemonic == "umlal" || Mnemonic == "vabal" ||
5797 Mnemonic == "vmlal" || Mnemonic == "vpadal" || Mnemonic == "vqdmlal" ||
5798 Mnemonic == "fmuls" || Mnemonic == "vmaxnm" || Mnemonic == "vminnm" ||
5799 Mnemonic == "vcvta" || Mnemonic == "vcvtn" || Mnemonic == "vcvtp" ||
5800 Mnemonic == "vcvtm" || Mnemonic == "vrinta" || Mnemonic == "vrintn" ||
5801 Mnemonic == "vrintp" || Mnemonic == "vrintm" || Mnemonic == "hvc" ||
5802 Mnemonic.startswith("vsel") || Mnemonic == "vins" || Mnemonic == "vmovx" ||
5803 Mnemonic == "bxns" || Mnemonic == "blxns" ||
5804 Mnemonic == "vudot" || Mnemonic == "vsdot" ||
5805 Mnemonic == "vcmla" || Mnemonic == "vcadd" ||
5806 Mnemonic == "vfmal" || Mnemonic == "vfmsl" ||
5807 Mnemonic == "wls" || Mnemonic == "le" || Mnemonic == "dls" ||
5808 Mnemonic == "csel" || Mnemonic == "csinc" ||
5809 Mnemonic == "csinv" || Mnemonic == "csneg" || Mnemonic == "cinc" ||
5810 Mnemonic == "cinv" || Mnemonic == "cneg" || Mnemonic == "cset" ||
5811 Mnemonic == "csetm")
5812 return Mnemonic;
5813
5814 // First, split out any predication code. Ignore mnemonics we know aren't
5815 // predicated but do have a carry-set and so weren't caught above.
5816 if (Mnemonic != "adcs" && Mnemonic != "bics" && Mnemonic != "movs" &&
5817 Mnemonic != "muls" && Mnemonic != "smlals" && Mnemonic != "smulls" &&
5818 Mnemonic != "umlals" && Mnemonic != "umulls" && Mnemonic != "lsls" &&
5819 Mnemonic != "sbcs" && Mnemonic != "rscs") {
5820 unsigned CC = ARMCondCodeFromString(Mnemonic.substr(Mnemonic.size()-2));
5821 if (CC != ~0U) {
5822 Mnemonic = Mnemonic.slice(0, Mnemonic.size() - 2);
5823 PredicationCode = CC;
5824 }
5825 }
5826
5827 // Next, determine if we have a carry setting bit. We explicitly ignore all
5828 // the instructions we know end in 's'.
5829 if (Mnemonic.endswith("s") &&
5830 !(Mnemonic == "cps" || Mnemonic == "mls" ||
5831 Mnemonic == "mrs" || Mnemonic == "smmls" || Mnemonic == "vabs" ||
5832 Mnemonic == "vcls" || Mnemonic == "vmls" || Mnemonic == "vmrs" ||
5833 Mnemonic == "vnmls" || Mnemonic == "vqabs" || Mnemonic == "vrecps" ||
5834 Mnemonic == "vrsqrts" || Mnemonic == "srs" || Mnemonic == "flds" ||
5835 Mnemonic == "fmrs" || Mnemonic == "fsqrts" || Mnemonic == "fsubs" ||
5836 Mnemonic == "fsts" || Mnemonic == "fcpys" || Mnemonic == "fdivs" ||
5837 Mnemonic == "fmuls" || Mnemonic == "fcmps" || Mnemonic == "fcmpzs" ||
5838 Mnemonic == "vfms" || Mnemonic == "vfnms" || Mnemonic == "fconsts" ||
5839 Mnemonic == "bxns" || Mnemonic == "blxns" ||
5840 (Mnemonic == "movs" && isThumb()))) {
5841 Mnemonic = Mnemonic.slice(0, Mnemonic.size() - 1);
5842 CarrySetting = true;
5843 }
5844
5845 // The "cps" instruction can have a interrupt mode operand which is glued into
5846 // the mnemonic. Check if this is the case, split it and parse the imod op
5847 if (Mnemonic.startswith("cps")) {
5848 // Split out any imod code.
5849 unsigned IMod =
5850 StringSwitch<unsigned>(Mnemonic.substr(Mnemonic.size()-2, 2))
5851 .Case("ie", ARM_PROC::IE)
5852 .Case("id", ARM_PROC::ID)
5853 .Default(~0U);
5854 if (IMod != ~0U) {
5855 Mnemonic = Mnemonic.slice(0, Mnemonic.size()-2);
5856 ProcessorIMod = IMod;
5857 }
5858 }
5859
5860 // The "it" instruction has the condition mask on the end of the mnemonic.
5861 if (Mnemonic.startswith("it")) {
5862 ITMask = Mnemonic.slice(2, Mnemonic.size());
5863 Mnemonic = Mnemonic.slice(0, 2);
5864 }
5865
5866 return Mnemonic;
5867}
5868
5869/// Given a canonical mnemonic, determine if the instruction ever allows
5870/// inclusion of carry set or predication code operands.
5871//
5872// FIXME: It would be nice to autogen this.
5873void ARMAsmParser::getMnemonicAcceptInfo(StringRef Mnemonic, StringRef FullInst,
5874 bool &CanAcceptCarrySet,
5875 bool &CanAcceptPredicationCode) {
5876 CanAcceptCarrySet =
5877 Mnemonic == "and" || Mnemonic == "lsl" || Mnemonic == "lsr" ||
5878 Mnemonic == "rrx" || Mnemonic == "ror" || Mnemonic == "sub" ||
5879 Mnemonic == "add" || Mnemonic == "adc" || Mnemonic == "mul" ||
5880 Mnemonic == "bic" || Mnemonic == "asr" || Mnemonic == "orr" ||
5881 Mnemonic == "mvn" || Mnemonic == "rsb" || Mnemonic == "rsc" ||
5882 Mnemonic == "orn" || Mnemonic == "sbc" || Mnemonic == "eor" ||
5883 Mnemonic == "neg" || Mnemonic == "vfm" || Mnemonic == "vfnm" ||
5884 (!isThumb() &&
5885 (Mnemonic == "smull" || Mnemonic == "mov" || Mnemonic == "mla" ||
5886 Mnemonic == "smlal" || Mnemonic == "umlal" || Mnemonic == "umull"));
5887
5888 if (Mnemonic == "bkpt" || Mnemonic == "cbnz" || Mnemonic == "setend" ||
5889 Mnemonic == "cps" || Mnemonic == "it" || Mnemonic == "cbz" ||
5890 Mnemonic == "trap" || Mnemonic == "hlt" || Mnemonic == "udf" ||
5891 Mnemonic.startswith("crc32") || Mnemonic.startswith("cps") ||
5892 Mnemonic.startswith("vsel") || Mnemonic == "vmaxnm" ||
5893 Mnemonic == "vminnm" || Mnemonic == "vcvta" || Mnemonic == "vcvtn" ||
5894 Mnemonic == "vcvtp" || Mnemonic == "vcvtm" || Mnemonic == "vrinta" ||
5895 Mnemonic == "vrintn" || Mnemonic == "vrintp" || Mnemonic == "vrintm" ||
5896 Mnemonic.startswith("aes") || Mnemonic == "hvc" || Mnemonic == "setpan" ||
5897 Mnemonic.startswith("sha1") || Mnemonic.startswith("sha256") ||
5898 (FullInst.startswith("vmull") && FullInst.endswith(".p64")) ||
5899 Mnemonic == "vmovx" || Mnemonic == "vins" ||
5900 Mnemonic == "vudot" || Mnemonic == "vsdot" ||
5901 Mnemonic == "vcmla" || Mnemonic == "vcadd" ||
5902 Mnemonic == "vfmal" || Mnemonic == "vfmsl" ||
5903 Mnemonic == "sb" || Mnemonic == "ssbb" ||
5904 Mnemonic == "pssbb" ||
5905 Mnemonic == "bfcsel" || Mnemonic == "wls" ||
5906 Mnemonic == "dls" || Mnemonic == "le" || Mnemonic == "csel" ||
5907 Mnemonic == "csinc" || Mnemonic == "csinv" || Mnemonic == "csneg" ||
5908 Mnemonic == "cinc" || Mnemonic == "cinv" || Mnemonic == "cneg" ||
5909 Mnemonic == "cset" || Mnemonic == "csetm") {
5910 // These mnemonics are never predicable
5911 CanAcceptPredicationCode = false;
5912 } else if (!isThumb()) {
5913 // Some instructions are only predicable in Thumb mode
5914 CanAcceptPredicationCode =
5915 Mnemonic != "cdp2" && Mnemonic != "clrex" && Mnemonic != "mcr2" &&
5916 Mnemonic != "mcrr2" && Mnemonic != "mrc2" && Mnemonic != "mrrc2" &&
5917 Mnemonic != "dmb" && Mnemonic != "dfb" && Mnemonic != "dsb" &&
5918 Mnemonic != "isb" && Mnemonic != "pld" && Mnemonic != "pli" &&
5919 Mnemonic != "pldw" && Mnemonic != "ldc2" && Mnemonic != "ldc2l" &&
5920 Mnemonic != "stc2" && Mnemonic != "stc2l" &&
5921 Mnemonic != "tsb" &&
5922 !Mnemonic.startswith("rfe") && !Mnemonic.startswith("srs");
5923 } else if (isThumbOne()) {
5924 if (hasV6MOps())
5925 CanAcceptPredicationCode = Mnemonic != "movs";
5926 else
5927 CanAcceptPredicationCode = Mnemonic != "nop" && Mnemonic != "movs";
5928 } else
5929 CanAcceptPredicationCode = true;
5930}
5931
5932// Some Thumb instructions have two operand forms that are not
5933// available as three operand, convert to two operand form if possible.
5934//
5935// FIXME: We would really like to be able to tablegen'erate this.
5936void ARMAsmParser::tryConvertingToTwoOperandForm(StringRef Mnemonic,
5937 bool CarrySetting,
5938 OperandVector &Operands) {
5939 if (Operands.size() != 6)
5940 return;
5941
5942 const auto &Op3 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]);
5943 auto &Op4 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]);
5944 if (!Op3.isReg() || !Op4.isReg())
5945 return;
5946
5947 auto Op3Reg = Op3.getReg();
5948 auto Op4Reg = Op4.getReg();
5949
5950 // For most Thumb2 cases we just generate the 3 operand form and reduce
5951 // it in processInstruction(), but the 3 operand form of ADD (t2ADDrr)
5952 // won't accept SP or PC so we do the transformation here taking care
5953 // with immediate range in the 'add sp, sp #imm' case.
5954 auto &Op5 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]);
5955 if (isThumbTwo()) {
5956 if (Mnemonic != "add")
5957 return;
5958 bool TryTransform = Op3Reg == ARM::PC || Op4Reg == ARM::PC ||
5959 (Op5.isReg() && Op5.getReg() == ARM::PC);
5960 if (!TryTransform) {
5961 TryTransform = (Op3Reg == ARM::SP || Op4Reg == ARM::SP ||
5962 (Op5.isReg() && Op5.getReg() == ARM::SP)) &&
5963 !(Op3Reg == ARM::SP && Op4Reg == ARM::SP &&
5964 Op5.isImm() && !Op5.isImm0_508s4());
5965 }
5966 if (!TryTransform)
5967 return;
5968 } else if (!isThumbOne())
5969 return;
5970
5971 if (!(Mnemonic == "add" || Mnemonic == "sub" || Mnemonic == "and" ||
5972 Mnemonic == "eor" || Mnemonic == "lsl" || Mnemonic == "lsr" ||
5973 Mnemonic == "asr" || Mnemonic == "adc" || Mnemonic == "sbc" ||
5974 Mnemonic == "ror" || Mnemonic == "orr" || Mnemonic == "bic"))
5975 return;
5976
5977 // If first 2 operands of a 3 operand instruction are the same
5978 // then transform to 2 operand version of the same instruction
5979 // e.g. 'adds r0, r0, #1' transforms to 'adds r0, #1'
5980 bool Transform = Op3Reg == Op4Reg;
5981
5982 // For communtative operations, we might be able to transform if we swap
5983 // Op4 and Op5. The 'ADD Rdm, SP, Rdm' form is already handled specially
5984 // as tADDrsp.
5985 const ARMOperand *LastOp = &Op5;
5986 bool Swap = false;
5987 if (!Transform && Op5.isReg() && Op3Reg == Op5.getReg() &&
5988 ((Mnemonic == "add" && Op4Reg != ARM::SP) ||
5989 Mnemonic == "and" || Mnemonic == "eor" ||
5990 Mnemonic == "adc" || Mnemonic == "orr")) {
5991 Swap = true;
5992 LastOp = &Op4;
5993 Transform = true;
5994 }
5995
5996 // If both registers are the same then remove one of them from
5997 // the operand list, with certain exceptions.
5998 if (Transform) {
5999 // Don't transform 'adds Rd, Rd, Rm' or 'sub{s} Rd, Rd, Rm' because the
6000 // 2 operand forms don't exist.
6001 if (((Mnemonic == "add" && CarrySetting) || Mnemonic == "sub") &&
6002 LastOp->isReg())
6003 Transform = false;
6004
6005 // Don't transform 'add/sub{s} Rd, Rd, #imm' if the immediate fits into
6006 // 3-bits because the ARMARM says not to.
6007 if ((Mnemonic == "add" || Mnemonic == "sub") && LastOp->isImm0_7())
6008 Transform = false;
6009 }
6010
6011 if (Transform) {
6012 if (Swap)
6013 std::swap(Op4, Op5);
6014 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + 3);
6015 }
6016}
6017
6018bool ARMAsmParser::shouldOmitCCOutOperand(StringRef Mnemonic,
6019 OperandVector &Operands) {
6020 // FIXME: This is all horribly hacky. We really need a better way to deal
6021 // with optional operands like this in the matcher table.
6022
6023 // The 'mov' mnemonic is special. One variant has a cc_out operand, while
6024 // another does not. Specifically, the MOVW instruction does not. So we
6025 // special case it here and remove the defaulted (non-setting) cc_out
6026 // operand if that's the instruction we're trying to match.
6027 //
6028 // We do this as post-processing of the explicit operands rather than just
6029 // conditionally adding the cc_out in the first place because we need
6030 // to check the type of the parsed immediate operand.
6031 if (Mnemonic == "mov" && Operands.size() > 4 && !isThumb() &&
6032 !static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isModImm() &&
6033 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isImm0_65535Expr() &&
6034 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0)
6035 return true;
6036
6037 // Register-register 'add' for thumb does not have a cc_out operand
6038 // when there are only two register operands.
6039 if (isThumb() && Mnemonic == "add" && Operands.size() == 5 &&
6040 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6041 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6042 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0)
6043 return true;
6044 // Register-register 'add' for thumb does not have a cc_out operand
6045 // when it's an ADD Rdm, SP, {Rdm|#imm0_255} instruction. We do
6046 // have to check the immediate range here since Thumb2 has a variant
6047 // that can handle a different range and has a cc_out operand.
6048 if (((isThumb() && Mnemonic == "add") ||
6049 (isThumbTwo() && Mnemonic == "sub")) &&
6050 Operands.size() == 6 && static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6051 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6052 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg() == ARM::SP &&
6053 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0 &&
6054 ((Mnemonic == "add" && static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isReg()) ||
6055 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isImm0_1020s4()))
6056 return true;
6057 // For Thumb2, add/sub immediate does not have a cc_out operand for the
6058 // imm0_4095 variant. That's the least-preferred variant when
6059 // selecting via the generic "add" mnemonic, so to know that we
6060 // should remove the cc_out operand, we have to explicitly check that
6061 // it's not one of the other variants. Ugh.
6062 if (isThumbTwo() && (Mnemonic == "add" || Mnemonic == "sub") &&
6063 Operands.size() == 6 && static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6064 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6065 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isImm()) {
6066 // Nest conditions rather than one big 'if' statement for readability.
6067 //
6068 // If both registers are low, we're in an IT block, and the immediate is
6069 // in range, we should use encoding T1 instead, which has a cc_out.
6070 if (inITBlock() &&
6071 isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg()) &&
6072 isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg()) &&
6073 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isImm0_7())
6074 return false;
6075 // Check against T3. If the second register is the PC, this is an
6076 // alternate form of ADR, which uses encoding T4, so check for that too.
6077 if (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg() != ARM::PC &&
6078 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isT2SOImm())
6079 return false;
6080
6081 // Otherwise, we use encoding T4, which does not have a cc_out
6082 // operand.
6083 return true;
6084 }
6085
6086 // The thumb2 multiply instruction doesn't have a CCOut register, so
6087 // if we have a "mul" mnemonic in Thumb mode, check if we'll be able to
6088 // use the 16-bit encoding or not.
6089 if (isThumbTwo() && Mnemonic == "mul" && Operands.size() == 6 &&
6090 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0 &&
6091 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6092 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6093 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isReg() &&
6094 // If the registers aren't low regs, the destination reg isn't the
6095 // same as one of the source regs, or the cc_out operand is zero
6096 // outside of an IT block, we have to use the 32-bit encoding, so
6097 // remove the cc_out operand.
6098 (!isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg()) ||
6099 !isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg()) ||
6100 !isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).getReg()) ||
6101 !inITBlock() || (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg() !=
6102 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).getReg() &&
6103 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg() !=
6104 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg())))
6105 return true;
6106
6107 // Also check the 'mul' syntax variant that doesn't specify an explicit
6108 // destination register.
6109 if (isThumbTwo() && Mnemonic == "mul" && Operands.size() == 5 &&
6110 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0 &&
6111 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6112 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6113 // If the registers aren't low regs or the cc_out operand is zero
6114 // outside of an IT block, we have to use the 32-bit encoding, so
6115 // remove the cc_out operand.
6116 (!isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg()) ||
6117 !isARMLowRegister(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg()) ||
6118 !inITBlock()))
6119 return true;
6120
6121 // Register-register 'add/sub' for thumb does not have a cc_out operand
6122 // when it's an ADD/SUB SP, #imm. Be lenient on count since there's also
6123 // the "add/sub SP, SP, #imm" version. If the follow-up operands aren't
6124 // right, this will result in better diagnostics (which operand is off)
6125 // anyway.
6126 if (isThumb() && (Mnemonic == "add" || Mnemonic == "sub") &&
6127 (Operands.size() == 5 || Operands.size() == 6) &&
6128 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6129 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg() == ARM::SP &&
6130 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).getReg() == 0 &&
6131 (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isImm() ||
6132 (Operands.size() == 6 &&
6133 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isImm())))
6134 return true;
6135
6136 return false;
6137}
6138
6139bool ARMAsmParser::shouldOmitPredicateOperand(StringRef Mnemonic,
6140 OperandVector &Operands) {
6141 // VRINT{Z, X} have a predicate operand in VFP, but not in NEON
6142 unsigned RegIdx = 3;
6143 if ((Mnemonic == "vrintz" || Mnemonic == "vrintx") &&
6144 (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).getToken() == ".f32" ||
6145 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).getToken() == ".f16")) {
6146 if (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isToken() &&
6147 (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getToken() == ".f32" ||
6148 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getToken() == ".f16"))
6149 RegIdx = 4;
6150
6151 if (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[RegIdx]).isReg() &&
6152 (ARMMCRegisterClasses[ARM::DPRRegClassID].contains(
6153 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[RegIdx]).getReg()) ||
6154 ARMMCRegisterClasses[ARM::QPRRegClassID].contains(
6155 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[RegIdx]).getReg())))
6156 return true;
6157 }
6158 return false;
6159}
6160
6161static bool isDataTypeToken(StringRef Tok) {
6162 return Tok == ".8" || Tok == ".16" || Tok == ".32" || Tok == ".64" ||
6163 Tok == ".i8" || Tok == ".i16" || Tok == ".i32" || Tok == ".i64" ||
6164 Tok == ".u8" || Tok == ".u16" || Tok == ".u32" || Tok == ".u64" ||
6165 Tok == ".s8" || Tok == ".s16" || Tok == ".s32" || Tok == ".s64" ||
6166 Tok == ".p8" || Tok == ".p16" || Tok == ".f32" || Tok == ".f64" ||
6167 Tok == ".f" || Tok == ".d";
6168}
6169
6170// FIXME: This bit should probably be handled via an explicit match class
6171// in the .td files that matches the suffix instead of having it be
6172// a literal string token the way it is now.
6173static bool doesIgnoreDataTypeSuffix(StringRef Mnemonic, StringRef DT) {
6174 return Mnemonic.startswith("vldm") || Mnemonic.startswith("vstm");
6175}
6176
6177static void applyMnemonicAliases(StringRef &Mnemonic,
6178 const FeatureBitset &Features,
6179 unsigned VariantID);
6180
6181// The GNU assembler has aliases of ldrd and strd with the second register
6182// omitted. We don't have a way to do that in tablegen, so fix it up here.
6183//
6184// We have to be careful to not emit an invalid Rt2 here, because the rest of
6185// the assmebly parser could then generate confusing diagnostics refering to
6186// it. If we do find anything that prevents us from doing the transformation we
6187// bail out, and let the assembly parser report an error on the instruction as
6188// it is written.
6189void ARMAsmParser::fixupGNULDRDAlias(StringRef Mnemonic,
6190 OperandVector &Operands) {
6191 if (Mnemonic != "ldrd" && Mnemonic != "strd")
6192 return;
6193 if (Operands.size() < 4)
6194 return;
6195
6196 ARMOperand &Op2 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]);
6197 ARMOperand &Op3 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]);
6198
6199 if (!Op2.isReg())
6200 return;
6201 if (!Op3.isMem())
6202 return;
6203
6204 const MCRegisterClass &GPR = MRI->getRegClass(ARM::GPRRegClassID);
6205 if (!GPR.contains(Op2.getReg()))
6206 return;
6207
6208 unsigned RtEncoding = MRI->getEncodingValue(Op2.getReg());
6209 if (!isThumb() && (RtEncoding & 1)) {
6210 // In ARM mode, the registers must be from an aligned pair, this
6211 // restriction does not apply in Thumb mode.
6212 return;
6213 }
6214 if (Op2.getReg() == ARM::PC)
6215 return;
6216 unsigned PairedReg = GPR.getRegister(RtEncoding + 1);
6217 if (!PairedReg || PairedReg == ARM::PC ||
6218 (PairedReg == ARM::SP && !hasV8Ops()))
6219 return;
6220
6221 Operands.insert(
6222 Operands.begin() + 3,
6223 ARMOperand::CreateReg(PairedReg, Op2.getStartLoc(), Op2.getEndLoc()));
6224}
6225
6226/// Parse an arm instruction mnemonic followed by its operands.
6227bool ARMAsmParser::ParseInstruction(ParseInstructionInfo &Info, StringRef Name,
6228 SMLoc NameLoc, OperandVector &Operands) {
6229 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser();
6230
6231 // Apply mnemonic aliases before doing anything else, as the destination
6232 // mnemonic may include suffices and we want to handle them normally.
6233 // The generic tblgen'erated code does this later, at the start of
6234 // MatchInstructionImpl(), but that's too late for aliases that include
6235 // any sort of suffix.
6236 const FeatureBitset &AvailableFeatures = getAvailableFeatures();
6237 unsigned AssemblerDialect = getParser().getAssemblerDialect();
6238 applyMnemonicAliases(Name, AvailableFeatures, AssemblerDialect);
6239
6240 // First check for the ARM-specific .req directive.
6241 if (Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Identifier) &&
6242 Parser.getTok().getIdentifier() == ".req") {
6243 parseDirectiveReq(Name, NameLoc);
6244 // We always return 'error' for this, as we're done with this
6245 // statement and don't need to match the 'instruction."
6246 return true;
6247 }
6248
6249 // Create the leading tokens for the mnemonic, split by '.' characters.
6250 size_t Start = 0, Next = Name.find('.');
6251 StringRef Mnemonic = Name.slice(Start, Next);
6252
6253 // Split out the predication code and carry setting flag from the mnemonic.
6254 unsigned PredicationCode;
6255 unsigned ProcessorIMod;
6256 bool CarrySetting;
6257 StringRef ITMask;
6258 Mnemonic = splitMnemonic(Mnemonic, PredicationCode, CarrySetting,
6259 ProcessorIMod, ITMask);
6260
6261 // In Thumb1, only the branch (B) instruction can be predicated.
6262 if (isThumbOne() && PredicationCode != ARMCC::AL && Mnemonic != "b") {
6263 return Error(NameLoc, "conditional execution not supported in Thumb1");
6264 }
6265
6266 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateToken(Mnemonic, NameLoc));
6267
6268 // Handle the mask for IT instructions. In ARMOperand and MCOperand,
6269 // this is stored in a format independent of the condition code: the
6270 // lowest set bit indicates the end of the encoding, and above that,
6271 // a 1 bit indicates 'else', and an 0 indicates 'then'. E.g.
6272 // IT -> 1000
6273 // ITx -> x100 (ITT -> 0100, ITE -> 1100)
6274 // ITxy -> xy10 (e.g. ITET -> 1010)
6275 // ITxyz -> xyz1 (e.g. ITEET -> 1101)
6276 if (Mnemonic == "it") {
6277 SMLoc Loc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + 2);
6278 if (ITMask.size() > 3) {
6279 return Error(Loc, "too many conditions on IT instruction");
6280 }
6281 unsigned Mask = 8;
6282 for (unsigned i = ITMask.size(); i != 0; --i) {
6283 char pos = ITMask[i - 1];
6284 if (pos != 't' && pos != 'e') {
6285 return Error(Loc, "illegal IT block condition mask '" + ITMask + "'");
6286 }
6287 Mask >>= 1;
6288 if (ITMask[i - 1] == 'e')
6289 Mask |= 8;
6290 }
6291 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateITMask(Mask, Loc));
6292 }
6293
6294 // FIXME: This is all a pretty gross hack. We should automatically handle
6295 // optional operands like this via tblgen.
6296
6297 // Next, add the CCOut and ConditionCode operands, if needed.
6298 //
6299 // For mnemonics which can ever incorporate a carry setting bit or predication
6300 // code, our matching model involves us always generating CCOut and
6301 // ConditionCode operands to match the mnemonic "as written" and then we let
6302 // the matcher deal with finding the right instruction or generating an
6303 // appropriate error.
6304 bool CanAcceptCarrySet, CanAcceptPredicationCode;
6305 getMnemonicAcceptInfo(Mnemonic, Name, CanAcceptCarrySet, CanAcceptPredicationCode);
6306
6307 // If we had a carry-set on an instruction that can't do that, issue an
6308 // error.
6309 if (!CanAcceptCarrySet && CarrySetting) {
6310 return Error(NameLoc, "instruction '" + Mnemonic +
6311 "' can not set flags, but 's' suffix specified");
6312 }
6313 // If we had a predication code on an instruction that can't do that, issue an
6314 // error.
6315 if (!CanAcceptPredicationCode && PredicationCode != ARMCC::AL) {
6316 return Error(NameLoc, "instruction '" + Mnemonic +
6317 "' is not predicable, but condition code specified");
6318 }
6319
6320 // Add the carry setting operand, if necessary.
6321 if (CanAcceptCarrySet) {
6322 SMLoc Loc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + Mnemonic.size());
6323 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateCCOut(CarrySetting ? ARM::CPSR : 0,
6324 Loc));
6325 }
6326
6327 // Add the predication code operand, if necessary.
6328 if (CanAcceptPredicationCode) {
6329 SMLoc Loc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + Mnemonic.size() +
6330 CarrySetting);
6331 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateCondCode(
6332 ARMCC::CondCodes(PredicationCode), Loc));
6333 }
6334
6335 // Add the processor imod operand, if necessary.
6336 if (ProcessorIMod) {
6337 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateImm(
6338 MCConstantExpr::create(ProcessorIMod, getContext()),
6339 NameLoc, NameLoc));
6340 } else if (Mnemonic == "cps" && isMClass()) {
6341 return Error(NameLoc, "instruction 'cps' requires effect for M-class");
6342 }
6343
6344 // Add the remaining tokens in the mnemonic.
6345 while (Next != StringRef::npos) {
6346 Start = Next;
6347 Next = Name.find('.', Start + 1);
6348 StringRef ExtraToken = Name.slice(Start, Next);
6349
6350 // Some NEON instructions have an optional datatype suffix that is
6351 // completely ignored. Check for that.
6352 if (isDataTypeToken(ExtraToken) &&
6353 doesIgnoreDataTypeSuffix(Mnemonic, ExtraToken))
6354 continue;
6355
6356 // For for ARM mode generate an error if the .n qualifier is used.
6357 if (ExtraToken == ".n" && !isThumb()) {
6358 SMLoc Loc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + Start);
6359 return Error(Loc, "instruction with .n (narrow) qualifier not allowed in "
6360 "arm mode");
6361 }
6362
6363 // The .n qualifier is always discarded as that is what the tables
6364 // and matcher expect. In ARM mode the .w qualifier has no effect,
6365 // so discard it to avoid errors that can be caused by the matcher.
6366 if (ExtraToken != ".n" && (isThumb() || ExtraToken != ".w")) {
6367 SMLoc Loc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + Start);
6368 Operands.push_back(ARMOperand::CreateToken(ExtraToken, Loc));
6369 }
6370 }
6371
6372 // Read the remaining operands.
6373 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) {
6374 // Read the first operand.
6375 if (parseOperand(Operands, Mnemonic)) {
6376 return true;
6377 }
6378
6379 while (parseOptionalToken(AsmToken::Comma)) {
6380 // Parse and remember the operand.
6381 if (parseOperand(Operands, Mnemonic)) {
6382 return true;
6383 }
6384 }
6385 }
6386
6387 if (parseToken(AsmToken::EndOfStatement, "unexpected token in argument list"))
6388 return true;
6389
6390 tryConvertingToTwoOperandForm(Mnemonic, CarrySetting, Operands);
6391
6392 // Some instructions, mostly Thumb, have forms for the same mnemonic that
6393 // do and don't have a cc_out optional-def operand. With some spot-checks
6394 // of the operand list, we can figure out which variant we're trying to
6395 // parse and adjust accordingly before actually matching. We shouldn't ever
6396 // try to remove a cc_out operand that was explicitly set on the
6397 // mnemonic, of course (CarrySetting == true). Reason number #317 the
6398 // table driven matcher doesn't fit well with the ARM instruction set.
6399 if (!CarrySetting && shouldOmitCCOutOperand(Mnemonic, Operands))
6400 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + 1);
6401
6402 // Some instructions have the same mnemonic, but don't always
6403 // have a predicate. Distinguish them here and delete the
6404 // predicate if needed.
6405 if (PredicationCode == ARMCC::AL &&
6406 shouldOmitPredicateOperand(Mnemonic, Operands))
6407 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + 1);
6408
6409 // ARM mode 'blx' need special handling, as the register operand version
6410 // is predicable, but the label operand version is not. So, we can't rely
6411 // on the Mnemonic based checking to correctly figure out when to put
6412 // a k_CondCode operand in the list. If we're trying to match the label
6413 // version, remove the k_CondCode operand here.
6414 if (!isThumb() && Mnemonic == "blx" && Operands.size() == 3 &&
6415 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).isImm())
6416 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + 1);
6417
6418 // Adjust operands of ldrexd/strexd to MCK_GPRPair.
6419 // ldrexd/strexd require even/odd GPR pair. To enforce this constraint,
6420 // a single GPRPair reg operand is used in the .td file to replace the two
6421 // GPRs. However, when parsing from asm, the two GRPs cannot be automatically
6422 // expressed as a GPRPair, so we have to manually merge them.
6423 // FIXME: We would really like to be able to tablegen'erate this.
6424 if (!isThumb() && Operands.size() > 4 &&
6425 (Mnemonic == "ldrexd" || Mnemonic == "strexd" || Mnemonic == "ldaexd" ||
6426 Mnemonic == "stlexd")) {
6427 bool isLoad = (Mnemonic == "ldrexd" || Mnemonic == "ldaexd");
6428 unsigned Idx = isLoad ? 2 : 3;
6429 ARMOperand &Op1 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[Idx]);
6430 ARMOperand &Op2 = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[Idx + 1]);
6431
6432 const MCRegisterClass& MRC = MRI->getRegClass(ARM::GPRRegClassID);
6433 // Adjust only if Op1 and Op2 are GPRs.
6434 if (Op1.isReg() && Op2.isReg() && MRC.contains(Op1.getReg()) &&
6435 MRC.contains(Op2.getReg())) {
6436 unsigned Reg1 = Op1.getReg();
6437 unsigned Reg2 = Op2.getReg();
6438 unsigned Rt = MRI->getEncodingValue(Reg1);
6439 unsigned Rt2 = MRI->getEncodingValue(Reg2);
6440
6441 // Rt2 must be Rt + 1 and Rt must be even.
6442 if (Rt + 1 != Rt2 || (Rt & 1)) {
6443 return Error(Op2.getStartLoc(),
6444 isLoad ? "destination operands must be sequential"
6445 : "source operands must be sequential");
6446 }
6447 unsigned NewReg = MRI->getMatchingSuperReg(Reg1, ARM::gsub_0,
6448 &(MRI->getRegClass(ARM::GPRPairRegClassID)));
6449 Operands[Idx] =
6450 ARMOperand::CreateReg(NewReg, Op1.getStartLoc(), Op2.getEndLoc());
6451 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + Idx + 1);
6452 }
6453 }
6454
6455 // GNU Assembler extension (compatibility).
6456 fixupGNULDRDAlias(Mnemonic, Operands);
6457
6458 // FIXME: As said above, this is all a pretty gross hack. This instruction
6459 // does not fit with other "subs" and tblgen.
6460 // Adjust operands of B9.3.19 SUBS PC, LR, #imm (Thumb2) system instruction
6461 // so the Mnemonic is the original name "subs" and delete the predicate
6462 // operand so it will match the table entry.
6463 if (isThumbTwo() && Mnemonic == "sub" && Operands.size() == 6 &&
6464 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isReg() &&
6465 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getReg() == ARM::PC &&
6466 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).isReg() &&
6467 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[4]).getReg() == ARM::LR &&
6468 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[5]).isImm()) {
6469 Operands.front() = ARMOperand::CreateToken(Name, NameLoc);
6470 Operands.erase(Operands.begin() + 1);
6471 }
6472 return false;
6473}
6474
6475// Validate context-sensitive operand constraints.
6476
6477// return 'true' if register list contains non-low GPR registers,
6478// 'false' otherwise. If Reg is in the register list or is HiReg, set
6479// 'containsReg' to true.
6480static bool checkLowRegisterList(const MCInst &Inst, unsigned OpNo,
6481 unsigned Reg, unsigned HiReg,
6482 bool &containsReg) {
6483 containsReg = false;
6484 for (unsigned i = OpNo; i < Inst.getNumOperands(); ++i) {
6485 unsigned OpReg = Inst.getOperand(i).getReg();
6486 if (OpReg == Reg)
6487 containsReg = true;
6488 // Anything other than a low register isn't legal here.
6489 if (!isARMLowRegister(OpReg) && (!HiReg || OpReg != HiReg))
6490 return true;
6491 }
6492 return false;
6493}
6494
6495// Check if the specified regisgter is in the register list of the inst,
6496// starting at the indicated operand number.
6497static bool listContainsReg(const MCInst &Inst, unsigned OpNo, unsigned Reg) {
6498 for (unsigned i = OpNo, e = Inst.getNumOperands(); i < e; ++i) {
6499 unsigned OpReg = Inst.getOperand(i).getReg();
6500 if (OpReg == Reg)
6501 return true;
6502 }
6503 return false;
6504}
6505
6506// Return true if instruction has the interesting property of being
6507// allowed in IT blocks, but not being predicable.
6508static bool instIsBreakpoint(const MCInst &Inst) {
6509 return Inst.getOpcode() == ARM::tBKPT ||
6510 Inst.getOpcode() == ARM::BKPT ||
6511 Inst.getOpcode() == ARM::tHLT ||
6512 Inst.getOpcode() == ARM::HLT;
6513}
6514
6515bool ARMAsmParser::validatetLDMRegList(const MCInst &Inst,
6516 const OperandVector &Operands,
6517 unsigned ListNo, bool IsARPop) {
6518 const ARMOperand &Op = static_cast<const ARMOperand &>(*Operands[ListNo]);
6519 bool HasWritebackToken = Op.isToken() && Op.getToken() == "!";
6520
6521 bool ListContainsSP = listContainsReg(Inst, ListNo, ARM::SP);
6522 bool ListContainsLR = listContainsReg(Inst, ListNo, ARM::LR);
6523 bool ListContainsPC = listContainsReg(Inst, ListNo, ARM::PC);
6524
6525 if (!IsARPop && ListContainsSP)
6526 return Error(Operands[ListNo + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6527 "SP may not be in the register list");
6528 else if (ListContainsPC && ListContainsLR)
6529 return Error(Operands[ListNo + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6530 "PC and LR may not be in the register list simultaneously");
6531 return false;
6532}
6533
6534bool ARMAsmParser::validatetSTMRegList(const MCInst &Inst,
6535 const OperandVector &Operands,
6536 unsigned ListNo) {
6537 const ARMOperand &Op = static_cast<const ARMOperand &>(*Operands[ListNo]);
6538 bool HasWritebackToken = Op.isToken() && Op.getToken() == "!";
6539
6540 bool ListContainsSP = listContainsReg(Inst, ListNo, ARM::SP);
6541 bool ListContainsPC = listContainsReg(Inst, ListNo, ARM::PC);
6542
6543 if (ListContainsSP && ListContainsPC)
6544 return Error(Operands[ListNo + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6545 "SP and PC may not be in the register list");
6546 else if (ListContainsSP)
6547 return Error(Operands[ListNo + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6548 "SP may not be in the register list");
6549 else if (ListContainsPC)
6550 return Error(Operands[ListNo + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6551 "PC may not be in the register list");
6552 return false;
6553}
6554
6555bool ARMAsmParser::validateLDRDSTRD(MCInst &Inst,
6556 const OperandVector &Operands,
6557 bool Load, bool ARMMode, bool Writeback) {
6558 unsigned RtIndex = Load || !Writeback ? 0 : 1;
6559 unsigned Rt = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(RtIndex).getReg());
6560 unsigned Rt2 = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(RtIndex + 1).getReg());
6561
6562 if (ARMMode) {
6563 // Rt can't be R14.
6564 if (Rt == 14)
6565 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6566 "Rt can't be R14");
6567
6568 // Rt must be even-numbered.
6569 if ((Rt & 1) == 1)
6570 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6571 "Rt must be even-numbered");
6572
6573 // Rt2 must be Rt + 1.
6574 if (Rt2 != Rt + 1) {
6575 if (Load)
6576 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6577 "destination operands must be sequential");
6578 else
6579 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6580 "source operands must be sequential");
6581 }
6582
6583 // FIXME: Diagnose m == 15
6584 // FIXME: Diagnose ldrd with m == t || m == t2.
6585 }
6586
6587 if (!ARMMode && Load) {
6588 if (Rt2 == Rt)
6589 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6590 "destination operands can't be identical");
6591 }
6592
6593 if (Writeback) {
6594 unsigned Rn = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(3).getReg());
6595
6596 if (Rn == Rt || Rn == Rt2) {
6597 if (Load)
6598 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6599 "base register needs to be different from destination "
6600 "registers");
6601 else
6602 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6603 "source register and base register can't be identical");
6604 }
6605
6606 // FIXME: Diagnose ldrd/strd with writeback and n == 15.
6607 // (Except the immediate form of ldrd?)
6608 }
6609
6610 return false;
6611}
6612
6613
6614// FIXME: We would really like to be able to tablegen'erate this.
6615bool ARMAsmParser::validateInstruction(MCInst &Inst,
6616 const OperandVector &Operands) {
6617 const MCInstrDesc &MCID = MII.get(Inst.getOpcode());
6618 SMLoc Loc = Operands[0]->getStartLoc();
6619
6620 // Check the IT block state first.
6621 // NOTE: BKPT and HLT instructions have the interesting property of being
6622 // allowed in IT blocks, but not being predicable. They just always execute.
6623 if (inITBlock() && !instIsBreakpoint(Inst)) {
6624 // The instruction must be predicable.
6625 if (!MCID.isPredicable())
6626 return Error(Loc, "instructions in IT block must be predicable");
6627 ARMCC::CondCodes Cond = ARMCC::CondCodes(
6628 Inst.getOperand(MCID.findFirstPredOperandIdx()).getImm());
6629 if (Cond != currentITCond()) {
6630 // Find the condition code Operand to get its SMLoc information.
6631 SMLoc CondLoc;
6632 for (unsigned I = 1; I < Operands.size(); ++I)
6633 if (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[I]).isCondCode())
6634 CondLoc = Operands[I]->getStartLoc();
6635 return Error(CondLoc, "incorrect condition in IT block; got '" +
6636 StringRef(ARMCondCodeToString(Cond)) +
6637 "', but expected '" +
6638 ARMCondCodeToString(currentITCond()) + "'");
6639 }
6640 // Check for non-'al' condition codes outside of the IT block.
6641 } else if (isThumbTwo() && MCID.isPredicable() &&
6642 Inst.getOperand(MCID.findFirstPredOperandIdx()).getImm() !=
6643 ARMCC::AL && Inst.getOpcode() != ARM::tBcc &&
6644 Inst.getOpcode() != ARM::t2Bcc &&
6645 Inst.getOpcode() != ARM::t2BFic) {
6646 return Error(Loc, "predicated instructions must be in IT block");
6647 } else if (!isThumb() && !useImplicitITARM() && MCID.isPredicable() &&
6648 Inst.getOperand(MCID.findFirstPredOperandIdx()).getImm() !=
6649 ARMCC::AL) {
6650 return Warning(Loc, "predicated instructions should be in IT block");
6651 } else if (!MCID.isPredicable()) {
6652 // Check the instruction doesn't have a predicate operand anyway
6653 // that it's not allowed to use. Sometimes this happens in order
6654 // to keep instructions the same shape even though one cannot
6655 // legally be predicated, e.g. vmul.f16 vs vmul.f32.
6656 for (unsigned i = 0, e = MCID.getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) {
6657 if (MCID.OpInfo[i].isPredicate()) {
6658 if (Inst.getOperand(i).getImm() != ARMCC::AL)
6659 return Error(Loc, "instruction is not predicable");
6660 break;
6661 }
6662 }
6663 }
6664
6665 // PC-setting instructions in an IT block, but not the last instruction of
6666 // the block, are UNPREDICTABLE.
6667 if (inExplicitITBlock() && !lastInITBlock() && isITBlockTerminator(Inst)) {
6668 return Error(Loc, "instruction must be outside of IT block or the last instruction in an IT block");
6669 }
6670
6671 const unsigned Opcode = Inst.getOpcode();
6672 switch (Opcode) {
6673 case ARM::t2IT: {
6674 // Encoding is unpredictable if it ever results in a notional 'NV'
6675 // predicate. Since we don't parse 'NV' directly this means an 'AL'
6676 // predicate with an "else" mask bit.
6677 unsigned Cond = Inst.getOperand(0).getImm();
6678 unsigned Mask = Inst.getOperand(1).getImm();
6679
6680 // Conditions only allowing a 't' are those with no set bit except
6681 // the lowest-order one that indicates the end of the sequence. In
6682 // other words, powers of 2.
6683 if (Cond == ARMCC::AL && countPopulation(Mask) != 1)
6684 return Error(Loc, "unpredictable IT predicate sequence");
6685 break;
6686 }
6687 case ARM::LDRD:
6688 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/true, /*ARMMode*/true,
6689 /*Writeback*/false))
6690 return true;
6691 break;
6692 case ARM::LDRD_PRE:
6693 case ARM::LDRD_POST:
6694 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/true, /*ARMMode*/true,
6695 /*Writeback*/true))
6696 return true;
6697 break;
6698 case ARM::t2LDRDi8:
6699 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/true, /*ARMMode*/false,
6700 /*Writeback*/false))
6701 return true;
6702 break;
6703 case ARM::t2LDRD_PRE:
6704 case ARM::t2LDRD_POST:
6705 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/true, /*ARMMode*/false,
6706 /*Writeback*/true))
6707 return true;
6708 break;
6709 case ARM::t2BXJ: {
6710 const unsigned RmReg = Inst.getOperand(0).getReg();
6711 // Rm = SP is no longer unpredictable in v8-A
6712 if (RmReg == ARM::SP && !hasV8Ops())
6713 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
6714 "r13 (SP) is an unpredictable operand to BXJ");
6715 return false;
6716 }
6717 case ARM::STRD:
6718 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/false, /*ARMMode*/true,
6719 /*Writeback*/false))
6720 return true;
6721 break;
6722 case ARM::STRD_PRE:
6723 case ARM::STRD_POST:
6724 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/false, /*ARMMode*/true,
6725 /*Writeback*/true))
6726 return true;
6727 break;
6728 case ARM::t2STRD_PRE:
6729 case ARM::t2STRD_POST:
6730 if (validateLDRDSTRD(Inst, Operands, /*Load*/false, /*ARMMode*/false,
6731 /*Writeback*/true))
6732 return true;
6733 break;
6734 case ARM::STR_PRE_IMM:
6735 case ARM::STR_PRE_REG:
6736 case ARM::t2STR_PRE:
6737 case ARM::STR_POST_IMM:
6738 case ARM::STR_POST_REG:
6739 case ARM::t2STR_POST:
6740 case ARM::STRH_PRE:
6741 case ARM::t2STRH_PRE:
6742 case ARM::STRH_POST:
6743 case ARM::t2STRH_POST:
6744 case ARM::STRB_PRE_IMM:
6745 case ARM::STRB_PRE_REG:
6746 case ARM::t2STRB_PRE:
6747 case ARM::STRB_POST_IMM:
6748 case ARM::STRB_POST_REG:
6749 case ARM::t2STRB_POST: {
6750 // Rt must be different from Rn.
6751 const unsigned Rt = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(1).getReg());
6752 const unsigned Rn = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(2).getReg());
6753
6754 if (Rt == Rn)
6755 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6756 "source register and base register can't be identical");
6757 return false;
6758 }
6759 case ARM::LDR_PRE_IMM:
6760 case ARM::LDR_PRE_REG:
6761 case ARM::t2LDR_PRE:
6762 case ARM::LDR_POST_IMM:
6763 case ARM::LDR_POST_REG:
6764 case ARM::t2LDR_POST:
6765 case ARM::LDRH_PRE:
6766 case ARM::t2LDRH_PRE:
6767 case ARM::LDRH_POST:
6768 case ARM::t2LDRH_POST:
6769 case ARM::LDRSH_PRE:
6770 case ARM::t2LDRSH_PRE:
6771 case ARM::LDRSH_POST:
6772 case ARM::t2LDRSH_POST:
6773 case ARM::LDRB_PRE_IMM:
6774 case ARM::LDRB_PRE_REG:
6775 case ARM::t2LDRB_PRE:
6776 case ARM::LDRB_POST_IMM:
6777 case ARM::LDRB_POST_REG:
6778 case ARM::t2LDRB_POST:
6779 case ARM::LDRSB_PRE:
6780 case ARM::t2LDRSB_PRE:
6781 case ARM::LDRSB_POST:
6782 case ARM::t2LDRSB_POST: {
6783 // Rt must be different from Rn.
6784 const unsigned Rt = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(0).getReg());
6785 const unsigned Rn = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(2).getReg());
6786
6787 if (Rt == Rn)
6788 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6789 "destination register and base register can't be identical");
6790 return false;
6791 }
6792 case ARM::SBFX:
6793 case ARM::t2SBFX:
6794 case ARM::UBFX:
6795 case ARM::t2UBFX: {
6796 // Width must be in range [1, 32-lsb].
6797 unsigned LSB = Inst.getOperand(2).getImm();
6798 unsigned Widthm1 = Inst.getOperand(3).getImm();
6799 if (Widthm1 >= 32 - LSB)
6800 return Error(Operands[5]->getStartLoc(),
6801 "bitfield width must be in range [1,32-lsb]");
6802 return false;
6803 }
6804 // Notionally handles ARM::tLDMIA_UPD too.
6805 case ARM::tLDMIA: {
6806 // If we're parsing Thumb2, the .w variant is available and handles
6807 // most cases that are normally illegal for a Thumb1 LDM instruction.
6808 // We'll make the transformation in processInstruction() if necessary.
6809 //
6810 // Thumb LDM instructions are writeback iff the base register is not
6811 // in the register list.
6812 unsigned Rn = Inst.getOperand(0).getReg();
6813 bool HasWritebackToken =
6814 (static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isToken() &&
6815 static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).getToken() == "!");
6816 bool ListContainsBase;
6817 if (checkLowRegisterList(Inst, 3, Rn, 0, ListContainsBase) && !isThumbTwo())
6818 return Error(Operands[3 + HasWritebackToken]->getStartLoc(),
6819 "registers must be in range r0-r7");
6820 // If we should have writeback, then there should be a '!' token.
6821 if (!ListContainsBase && !HasWritebackToken && !isThumbTwo())
6822 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
6823 "writeback operator '!' expected");
6824 // If we should not have writeback, there must not be a '!'. This is
6825 // true even for the 32-bit wide encodings.
6826 if (ListContainsBase && HasWritebackToken)
6827 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6828 "writeback operator '!' not allowed when base register "
6829 "in register list");
6830
6831 if (validatetLDMRegList(Inst, Operands, 3))
6832 return true;
6833 break;
6834 }
6835 case ARM::LDMIA_UPD:
6836 case ARM::LDMDB_UPD:
6837 case ARM::LDMIB_UPD:
6838 case ARM::LDMDA_UPD:
6839 // ARM variants loading and updating the same register are only officially
6840 // UNPREDICTABLE on v7 upwards. Goodness knows what they did before.
6841 if (!hasV7Ops())
6842 break;
6843 if (listContainsReg(Inst, 3, Inst.getOperand(0).getReg()))
6844 return Error(Operands.back()->getStartLoc(),
6845 "writeback register not allowed in register list");
6846 break;
6847 case ARM::t2LDMIA:
6848 case ARM::t2LDMDB:
6849 if (validatetLDMRegList(Inst, Operands, 3))
6850 return true;
6851 break;
6852 case ARM::t2STMIA:
6853 case ARM::t2STMDB:
6854 if (validatetSTMRegList(Inst, Operands, 3))
6855 return true;
6856 break;
6857 case ARM::t2LDMIA_UPD:
6858 case ARM::t2LDMDB_UPD:
6859 case ARM::t2STMIA_UPD:
6860 case ARM::t2STMDB_UPD:
6861 if (listContainsReg(Inst, 3, Inst.getOperand(0).getReg()))
6862 return Error(Operands.back()->getStartLoc(),
6863 "writeback register not allowed in register list");
6864
6865 if (Opcode == ARM::t2LDMIA_UPD || Opcode == ARM::t2LDMDB_UPD) {
6866 if (validatetLDMRegList(Inst, Operands, 3))
6867 return true;
6868 } else {
6869 if (validatetSTMRegList(Inst, Operands, 3))
6870 return true;
6871 }
6872 break;
6873
6874 case ARM::sysLDMIA_UPD:
6875 case ARM::sysLDMDA_UPD:
6876 case ARM::sysLDMDB_UPD:
6877 case ARM::sysLDMIB_UPD:
6878 if (!listContainsReg(Inst, 3, ARM::PC))
6879 return Error(Operands[4]->getStartLoc(),
6880 "writeback register only allowed on system LDM "
6881 "if PC in register-list");
6882 break;
6883 case ARM::sysSTMIA_UPD:
6884 case ARM::sysSTMDA_UPD:
6885 case ARM::sysSTMDB_UPD:
6886 case ARM::sysSTMIB_UPD:
6887 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
6888 "system STM cannot have writeback register");
6889 case ARM::tMUL:
6890 // The second source operand must be the same register as the destination
6891 // operand.
6892 //
6893 // In this case, we must directly check the parsed operands because the
6894 // cvtThumbMultiply() function is written in such a way that it guarantees
6895 // this first statement is always true for the new Inst. Essentially, the
6896 // destination is unconditionally copied into the second source operand
6897 // without checking to see if it matches what we actually parsed.
6898 if (Operands.size() == 6 && (((ARMOperand &)*Operands[3]).getReg() !=
6899 ((ARMOperand &)*Operands[5]).getReg()) &&
6900 (((ARMOperand &)*Operands[3]).getReg() !=
6901 ((ARMOperand &)*Operands[4]).getReg())) {
6902 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
6903 "destination register must match source register");
6904 }
6905 break;
6906
6907 // Like for ldm/stm, push and pop have hi-reg handling version in Thumb2,
6908 // so only issue a diagnostic for thumb1. The instructions will be
6909 // switched to the t2 encodings in processInstruction() if necessary.
6910 case ARM::tPOP: {
6911 bool ListContainsBase;
6912 if (checkLowRegisterList(Inst, 2, 0, ARM::PC, ListContainsBase) &&
6913 !isThumbTwo())
6914 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
6915 "registers must be in range r0-r7 or pc");
6916 if (validatetLDMRegList(Inst, Operands, 2, !isMClass()))
6917 return true;
6918 break;
6919 }
6920 case ARM::tPUSH: {
6921 bool ListContainsBase;
6922 if (checkLowRegisterList(Inst, 2, 0, ARM::LR, ListContainsBase) &&
6923 !isThumbTwo())
6924 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
6925 "registers must be in range r0-r7 or lr");
6926 if (validatetSTMRegList(Inst, Operands, 2))
6927 return true;
6928 break;
6929 }
6930 case ARM::tSTMIA_UPD: {
6931 bool ListContainsBase, InvalidLowList;
6932 InvalidLowList = checkLowRegisterList(Inst, 4, Inst.getOperand(0).getReg(),
6933 0, ListContainsBase);
6934 if (InvalidLowList && !isThumbTwo())
6935 return Error(Operands[4]->getStartLoc(),
6936 "registers must be in range r0-r7");
6937
6938 // This would be converted to a 32-bit stm, but that's not valid if the
6939 // writeback register is in the list.
6940 if (InvalidLowList && ListContainsBase)
6941 return Error(Operands[4]->getStartLoc(),
6942 "writeback operator '!' not allowed when base register "
6943 "in register list");
6944
6945 if (validatetSTMRegList(Inst, Operands, 4))
6946 return true;
6947 break;
6948 }
6949 case ARM::tADDrSP:
6950 // If the non-SP source operand and the destination operand are not the
6951 // same, we need thumb2 (for the wide encoding), or we have an error.
6952 if (!isThumbTwo() &&
6953 Inst.getOperand(0).getReg() != Inst.getOperand(2).getReg()) {
6954 return Error(Operands[4]->getStartLoc(),
6955 "source register must be the same as destination");
6956 }
6957 break;
6958
6959 case ARM::t2ADDri:
6960 case ARM::t2ADDri12:
6961 case ARM::t2ADDrr:
6962 case ARM::t2ADDrs:
6963 case ARM::t2SUBri:
6964 case ARM::t2SUBri12:
6965 case ARM::t2SUBrr:
6966 case ARM::t2SUBrs:
6967 if (Inst.getOperand(0).getReg() == ARM::SP &&
6968 Inst.getOperand(1).getReg() != ARM::SP)
6969 return Error(Operands[4]->getStartLoc(),
6970 "source register must be sp if destination is sp");
6971 break;
6972
6973 // Final range checking for Thumb unconditional branch instructions.
6974 case ARM::tB:
6975 if (!(static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2])).isSignedOffset<11, 1>())
6976 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(), "branch target out of range");
6977 break;
6978 case ARM::t2B: {
6979 int op = (Operands[2]->isImm()) ? 2 : 3;
6980 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[op]).isSignedOffset<24, 1>())
6981 return Error(Operands[op]->getStartLoc(), "branch target out of range");
6982 break;
6983 }
6984 // Final range checking for Thumb conditional branch instructions.
6985 case ARM::tBcc:
6986 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).isSignedOffset<8, 1>())
6987 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(), "branch target out of range");
6988 break;
6989 case ARM::t2Bcc: {
6990 int Op = (Operands[2]->isImm()) ? 2 : 3;
6991 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[Op]).isSignedOffset<20, 1>())
6992 return Error(Operands[Op]->getStartLoc(), "branch target out of range");
6993 break;
6994 }
6995 case ARM::tCBZ:
6996 case ARM::tCBNZ: {
6997 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).isUnsignedOffset<6, 1>())
6998 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(), "branch target out of range");
6999 break;
7000 }
7001 case ARM::MOVi16:
7002 case ARM::MOVTi16:
7003 case ARM::t2MOVi16:
7004 case ARM::t2MOVTi16:
7005 {
7006 // We want to avoid misleadingly allowing something like "mov r0, <symbol>"
7007 // especially when we turn it into a movw and the expression <symbol> does
7008 // not have a :lower16: or :upper16 as part of the expression. We don't
7009 // want the behavior of silently truncating, which can be unexpected and
7010 // lead to bugs that are difficult to find since this is an easy mistake
7011 // to make.
7012 int i = (Operands[3]->isImm()) ? 3 : 4;
7013 ARMOperand &Op = static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[i]);
7014 const MCConstantExpr *CE = dyn_cast<MCConstantExpr>(Op.getImm());
7015 if (CE) break;
7016 const MCExpr *E = dyn_cast<MCExpr>(Op.getImm());
7017 if (!E) break;
7018 const ARMMCExpr *ARM16Expr = dyn_cast<ARMMCExpr>(E);
7019 if (!ARM16Expr || (ARM16Expr->getKind() != ARMMCExpr::VK_ARM_HI16 &&
7020 ARM16Expr->getKind() != ARMMCExpr::VK_ARM_LO16))
7021 return Error(
7022 Op.getStartLoc(),
7023 "immediate expression for mov requires :lower16: or :upper16");
7024 break;
7025 }
7026 case ARM::HINT:
7027 case ARM::t2HINT: {
7028 unsigned Imm8 = Inst.getOperand(0).getImm();
7029 unsigned Pred = Inst.getOperand(1).getImm();
7030 // ESB is not predicable (pred must be AL). Without the RAS extension, this
7031 // behaves as any other unallocated hint.
7032 if (Imm8 == 0x10 && Pred != ARMCC::AL && hasRAS())
7033 return Error(Operands[1]->getStartLoc(), "instruction 'esb' is not "
7034 "predicable, but condition "
7035 "code specified");
7036 if (Imm8 == 0x14 && Pred != ARMCC::AL)
7037 return Error(Operands[1]->getStartLoc(), "instruction 'csdb' is not "
7038 "predicable, but condition "
7039 "code specified");
7040 break;
7041 }
7042 case ARM::t2WLS: {
7043 int idx = Opcode == ARM::t2WLS ? 3 : 4;
7044 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[idx]).isUnsignedOffset<11, 1>())
7045 return Error(Operands[idx]->getStartLoc(),
7046 "loop end is out of range or not a positive multiple of 2");
7047 break;
7048 }
7049 case ARM::t2LEUpdate: {
7050 if (Inst.getOperand(2).isImm() &&
7051 !(Inst.getOperand(2).getImm() < 0 &&
7052 Inst.getOperand(2).getImm() >= -4094 &&
7053 (Inst.getOperand(2).getImm() & 1) == 0))
7054 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
7055 "loop start is out of range or not a negative multiple of 2");
7056 break;
7057 }
7058 case ARM::t2BFi:
7059 case ARM::t2BFr:
7060 case ARM::t2BFLi:
7061 case ARM::t2BFLr: {
7062 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).isUnsignedOffset<4, 1>() ||
7063 (Inst.getOperand(0).isImm() && Inst.getOperand(0).getImm() == 0))
7064 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
7065 "branch location out of range or not a multiple of 2");
7066
7067 if (Opcode == ARM::t2BFi) {
7068 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isSignedOffset<16, 1>())
7069 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
7070 "branch target out of range or not a multiple of 2");
7071 } else if (Opcode == ARM::t2BFLi) {
7072 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[3]).isSignedOffset<18, 1>())
7073 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
7074 "branch target out of range or not a multiple of 2");
7075 }
7076 break;
7077 }
7078 case ARM::t2BFic: {
7079 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[1]).isUnsignedOffset<4, 1>() ||
7080 (Inst.getOperand(0).isImm() && Inst.getOperand(0).getImm() == 0))
7081 return Error(Operands[1]->getStartLoc(),
7082 "branch location out of range or not a multiple of 2");
7083
7084 if (!static_cast<ARMOperand &>(*Operands[2]).isSignedOffset<16, 1>())
7085 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
7086 "branch target out of range or not a multiple of 2");
7087
7088 assert(Inst.getOperand(0).isImm() == Inst.getOperand(2).isImm() &&
7089 "branch location and else branch target should either both be "
7090 "immediates or both labels");
7091
7092 if (Inst.getOperand(0).isImm() && Inst.getOperand(2).isImm()) {
7093 int Diff = Inst.getOperand(2).getImm() - Inst.getOperand(0).getImm();
7094 if (Diff != 4 && Diff != 2)
7095 return Error(
7096 Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
7097 "else branch target must be 2 or 4 greater than the branch location");
7098 }
7099 break;
7100 }
7101 case ARM::t2CLRM: {
7102 for (unsigned i = 2; i < Inst.getNumOperands(); i++) {
7103 if (Inst.getOperand(i).isReg() &&
7104 !ARMMCRegisterClasses[ARM::GPRwithAPSRnospRegClassID].contains(
7105 Inst.getOperand(i).getReg())) {
7106 return Error(Operands[2]->getStartLoc(),
7107 "invalid register in register list. Valid registers are "
7108 "r0-r12, lr/r14 and APSR.");
7109 }
7110 }
7111 break;
7112 }
7113 case ARM::DSB:
7114 case ARM::t2DSB: {
7115
7116 if (Inst.getNumOperands() < 2)
7117 break;
7118
7119 unsigned Option = Inst.getOperand(0).getImm();
7120 unsigned Pred = Inst.getOperand(1).getImm();
7121
7122 // SSBB and PSSBB (DSB #0|#4) are not predicable (pred must be AL).
7123 if (Option == 0 && Pred != ARMCC::AL)
7124 return Error(Operands[1]->getStartLoc(),
7125 "instruction 'ssbb' is not predicable, but condition code "
7126 "specified");
7127 if (Option == 4 && Pred != ARMCC::AL)
7128 return Error(Operands[1]->getStartLoc(),
7129 "instruction 'pssbb' is not predicable, but condition code "
7130 "specified");
7131 break;
7132 }
7133 case ARM::VMOVRRS: {
7134 // Source registers must be sequential.
7135 const unsigned Sm = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(2).getReg());
7136 const unsigned Sm1 = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(3).getReg());
7137 if (Sm1 != Sm + 1)
7138 return Error(Operands[5]->getStartLoc(),
7139 "source operands must be sequential");
7140 break;
7141 }
7142 case ARM::VMOVSRR: {
7143 // Destination registers must be sequential.
7144 const unsigned Sm = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(0).getReg());
7145 const unsigned Sm1 = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(1).getReg());
7146 if (Sm1 != Sm + 1)
7147 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
7148 "destination operands must be sequential");
7149 break;
7150 }
7151 case ARM::VLDMDIA:
7152 case ARM::VSTMDIA: {
7153 ARMOperand &Op = static_cast<ARMOperand&>(*Operands[3]);
7154 auto &RegList = Op.getRegList();
7155 if (RegList.size() < 1 || RegList.size() > 16)
7156 return Error(Operands[3]->getStartLoc(),
7157 "list of registers must be at least 1 and at most 16");
7158 break;
7159 }
7160 }
7161
7162 return false;
7163}

7165static unsigned getRealVSTOpcode(unsigned Opc, unsigned &Spacing) {
7166 switch(Opc) {

7168 // VST1LN

7170 case ARM::VST1LNdWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VST1LNd16_UPD;
7171 case ARM::VST1LNdWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VST1LNd32_UPD;

7259 case ARM::VST4dWB_register_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VST4d8_UPD;

7274static unsigned getRealVLDOpcode(unsigned Opc, unsigned &Spacing) {
7275 switch(Opc) {
7276 default: llvm_unreachable("unexpected opcode!");
7277 // VLD1LN
7278 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_fixed_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd8_UPD;
7279 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd16_UPD;
7280 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd32_UPD;
7281 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_register_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd8_UPD;
7282 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_register_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd16_UPD;
7283 case ARM::VLD1LNdWB_register_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd32_UPD;
7284 case ARM::VLD1LNdAsm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd8;
7285 case ARM::VLD1LNdAsm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd16;
7286 case ARM::VLD1LNdAsm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD1LNd32;
7287

7290 case ARM::VLD2LNdWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd16_UPD;
7291 case ARM::VLD2LNdWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd32_UPD;
7292 case ARM::VLD2LNqWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNq16_UPD;
7293 case ARM::VLD2LNqWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD2LNq32_UPD;
7294 case ARM::VLD2LNdWB_register_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd8_UPD;
7295 case ARM::VLD2LNdWB_register_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd16_UPD;
7296 case ARM::VLD2LNdWB_register_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd32_UPD;
7297 case ARM::VLD2LNqWB_register_Asm_16: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD2LNq16_UPD;
7298 case ARM::VLD2LNqWB_register_Asm_32: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD2LNq32_UPD;
7299 case ARM::VLD2LNdAsm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd8;
7300 case ARM::VLD2LNdAsm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd16;
7301 case ARM::VLD2LNdAsm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD2LNd32;
7302 case ARM::VLD2LNqAsm_16: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD2LNq16;
7303 case ARM::VLD2LNqAsm_32: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD2LNq32;

7308 case ARM::VLD3DUPdWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd32_UPD;
7309 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_fixed_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPq8_UPD;
7310 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq16_UPD;
7311 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq32_UPD;
7312 case ARM::VLD3DUPdWB_register_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd8_UPD;
7313 case ARM::VLD3DUPdWB_register_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd16_UPD;
7314 case ARM::VLD3DUPdWB_register_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd32_UPD;
7315 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_register_Asm_8: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq8_UPD;
7316 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_register_Asm_16: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq16_UPD;
7317 case ARM::VLD3DUPqWB_register_Asm_32: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq32_UPD;
7318 case ARM::VLD3DUPdAsm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd8;
7319 case ARM::VLD3DUPdAsm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd16;
7320 case ARM::VLD3DUPdAsm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3DUPd32;
7321 case ARM::VLD3DUPqAsm_8: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq8;
7322 case ARM::VLD3DUPqAsm_16: Spacing = 2; return ARM::VLD3DUPq16;

7325 // VLD3LN
7326 case ARM::VLD3LNdWB_fixed_Asm_8: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3LNd8_UPD;
7327 case ARM::VLD3LNdWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3LNd16_UPD;
7328 case ARM::VLD3LNdWB_fixed_Asm_32: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3LNd32_UPD;
7329 case ARM::VLD3LNqWB_fixed_Asm_16: Spacing = 1; return ARM::VLD3LNq16_UPD;
